M5: take: all auto-cap + --max-rows-per-component override

Two-part fix for the materialization-time edge surfaced during M5
validation: a recipe with all 8 components on take: all hangs curate
for 25+ minutes on heavy code corpora.

* recipe_draft.DEFAULT_DRAFT_TAKE_CAP=5000 + _cap_take() swap any
  take: "all" for the default cap at draft-write time and append a
  caveat that names the cap, explains the rationale, and tells the
  reader how to lift it (edit take: all or pass --max-rows-per-component).
  Explicit integer take values pass through verbatim. Tests cover
  both paths.

* curate gains --max-rows-per-component N. Plumbed through run_curate
  -> _materialize_component as max_rows_override. Lowers but NEVER
  raises the recipe's take value (recipe is the source of truth).
  Tests cover: cap take=all, lower an explicit take, and the
  never-raise invariant.

* Live verified on the M5 hallucinated-API recipe (8 components,
  several large code corpora): a previously-killed 25+ min curate
  now ships in 62 s, 3941 rows, full audit-ready output (filter DSL
  + leakage-aware splits + classified failures all working).

* docs/cli.md gets the new flag + an updated --out description for
  decompose (file vs directory routing).
* docs/getting-started.md walkthrough now shows take: 5000 with the
  auto-cap callout instead of take: all.

298 unit tests passing (added 5). mypy strict + ruff clean.

